		<item>
		<title>Bunker market ‘tight and firm’, waiting on Middle East developments</title>
		<link>https://ship.energy/energy/bunker-market-tight-and-firm-waiting-on-middle-east-developments/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Ian Taylor]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Fri, 06 Mar 2026 11:29:09 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Energy]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Fossil Fuels]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://ship.energy/?p=167169</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[The Marine Fuels Alliance (MFA) has informed ship.energy that its contacts in the supply community have reported that the bunker market is ‘tight and firm’, with players keeping a close eye on Middle East developments. In the Middle East region itself, sources told the MFA that Fujairah bunkering operations are relatively ‘normal’ and supply is available in most ports in the Persian Gulf – with the obvious exception of ports in Iran. Operations are also said to be ‘limited’ in Iraq. There have also been significant knock-on effects in other bunker markets – and India has been a notable case [&#8230;]]]></description>
