		<item>
		<title>Middle East crude oil futures and physical barrel prices top $100 </title>
		<link>https://ship.energy/information/middle-east-crude-oil-futures-and-physical-barrel-prices-top-100/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Lesley Bankes-Hughes]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Fri, 06 Mar 2026 11:26:25 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Energy]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Fossil Fuels]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Information]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Regional]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://ship.energy/?p=167177</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Middle East crude oil benchmarks Murban, DME Oman and Dubai have exceeded $100 per barrel (p/b) today (6 March) on both futures and physical markets. Analysts had been expecting prices to soar above $100 following the US/Israeli strike against Iran last Saturday and Iran’s retaliatory action. Fears over military strikes have effectively suspended the majority of vessel transits through the Strait of Hormuz which is the conduit for some 15% of global oil supply and 20% of global LNG demand. Oil prices are on the march again today. At time of writing, Brent crude futures were up to $87.27 per [&#8230;]]]></description>
