		<item>
		<title>EU maritime and ports strategies welcomed by shipping industry bodies</title>
		<link>https://ship.energy/policy/eu-maritime-ports-strategy-shipping-industry-port-reactions/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Ariane Morrissey]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Fri, 06 Mar 2026 11:21:56 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Information]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Policy]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Ports]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Regional]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://ship.energy/?p=167161</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Ports and associations representing shipowners and ferry operators have responded positively to the new Industrial Maritime Strategy and Ports Strategy that were adopted this week by the European Commission. The Industrial Maritime Strategy, announced on Wednesday (4 March), introduces measures to boost Europe’s maritime manufacturing capabilities and to strengthen the competitiveness and sustainability of shipping. It includes initiatives to simplify reporting and administrative procedures and a commitment to reinforce the EU’s engagement at IMO on global maritime standards. The strategy was ‘strongly endorsed’ by Interferry, the global trade association representing the ferry industry, which applauded the push for member states [&#8230;]]]></description>
